# Pudding #66: The Interdependence

*Not left or right. A more effective team.*

---

## At a Glance

The Founder calls himself a Patriotic Interdependentalist. That is not a party. It is a philosophy.

Independence says: "I do not need you." Dependence says: "I cannot function without you." Interdependence says: "I can stand on my own, and I choose to stand with you — because we are both stronger that way."

Every system in Liana Banyan is built on this idea. The eye cannot say to the hand, "I don't need you." That is scripture. It is also economics.

---

## More Info

### Why Not Independence?

American culture glorifies independence. The self-made man. The lone entrepreneur. Pull yourself up by your bootstraps.

But nobody is self-made. The farmer who grows your food depends on the trucker who delivers it. The trucker depends on the mechanic who fixes the truck. The mechanic depends on the school that trained her. The school depends on the taxes that fund it. The taxes depend on the economy that generates them. The economy depends on the farmer.

Independence is a myth. It is a useful myth for platforms that want to extract value from individuals — "you're on your own, and we're here to help (for 30% of your revenue)." But it is a myth.

### Why Not Dependence?

Dependence is the opposite trap. It says: "I cannot survive without the platform." This is how extractive platforms maintain power. Uber drivers depend on Uber for riders. Amazon sellers depend on Amazon for customers. The platform controls the relationship because the individual cannot function without it.

Cooperative economics rejects this too. A member of Liana Banyan is not dependent on the cooperative. They can leave anytime. They can sell on Etsy, on their own website, at farmers markets. The cooperative is one tool in their toolkit — not the only one.

### Why Interdependence?

Interdependence is the third option. It says: "We are each capable on our own. We choose to work together because cooperation produces outcomes that neither of us can achieve alone."

A leather crafter can sell wallets without the cooperative. But through the cooperative, they get:
- Cooperative Purchasing that reduces their material costs by 30-40%
- Design Democracy that validates their designs before production
- A Treasure Map that plans their business
- A Cue Card that markets their product
- A Pioneer Node network that can scale their production
- A Beacon community that provides local customers

None of these require the crafter to surrender independence. They require the crafter to participate — to contribute their skills, their votes, their backing, their presence. In exchange, they receive capabilities they could not build alone.

---

## Full Detail

### HEOHO — The Interdependence Principle

HEOHO stands for "Help Each Other Help Ourselves." It is the cooperative's operating philosophy, distilled to six words.

Not "help each other" (which implies charity). Not "help ourselves" (which implies isolation). Help each other *help ourselves*. The assistance flows in a circle. You help me become more capable. I help you become more capable. We are both stronger. Neither of us is diminished.

This is not collectivism. Collectivism subordinates the individual to the group. Interdependence preserves individual agency while recognizing that agency is amplified by cooperation. You keep your business. You keep your profits. You keep your autonomy. You also gain access to a cooperative infrastructure that makes your business more resilient, more efficient, and more connected.

### Interdependence in Architecture

The cooperative's technical architecture reflects interdependence:

**Bridges, not walls.** The Outbound Commerce Bridge sends your customers to your Etsy shop. The cooperative does not trap you. It connects you.

**Cost+20%, not extraction.** The margin covers the cooperative's costs. Everything else goes to you. The cooperative succeeds when you succeed — not when it takes more from you.

**Marks, not money.** Reputation is earned through contribution, not purchased with capital. Your standing in the cooperative reflects what you have given, not what you can afford.

**Captains, not managers.** Leaders are members who serve, not authorities who control. They show up first. They do not tell you what to do.

**Star Chamber, not algorithms.** Disputes are resolved by peers, not by automated systems designed to minimize the platform's liability.

Every architectural decision asks the same question: does this make members more capable, or more dependent? If it makes them dependent, it gets redesigned.

### The Patriotic Part

"Patriotic" is deliberate. The Founder is an Army veteran. He believes in the country — not the government of the moment, not the politics of the moment, but the foundational idea that people can govern themselves.

A cooperative is self-governance applied to economics. Members vote. Members lead. Members resolve disputes. Members decide what gets built. This is not anti-capitalist. It is not anti-government. It is pro-participation. It says: the economy works better when the people in it have a real say in how it runs.

Not left or right. A more effective team.

That is interdependence. That is HEOHO. That is the cooperative.

